title TUBE0 lands GREEN -- the Glow app-manifest mold, and a real pre-existing RED found along the way
prompt Keaton asked to switch back to Sonnet 5 1M Low and keep going -- picking up the prior plan's own recommendation: build TUBE0, the app-manifest mold, as the reachable next step. A second message arrived mid-build asking a broader strategic question (what to implement/port into Glow next, whether the rune/syntax spec is complete enough for the SLC mission, whether to start reference-grade docs and beginner tutorials) while the parity suite ran in the background.
think Read linengrow/pool_host_seam.rye and its witness, plus caravan/capabilities.rye in full, before writing anything -- wanted the manifest's own shape to reuse Pool's existing conventions exactly (bounded fixed arrays, invariant comments naming the exact bound, assert-heavy construction) rather than inventing a parallel style. Found capabilities.rye already names right_read/write/exec/net/device as bitmask constants -- reused these directly for a manifest's own DeclaredCapability rather than defining a second vocabulary for the same idea, a real sameness choice named explicitly in the module's own header comment.
think Designed validation as construction, not a separate step: build() returns ManifestError!Manifest, so there is no code path anywhere that produces a half-checked Manifest value -- a Manifest that exists at all is by construction well-formed, mirroring the rune brief's own "checked at expansion, never merely trusted" discipline for a bounded trap's hidden counter. Chose the malformed cases to refuse by working backward from what "well-formed" must mean for an app that will eventually be admitted by Pool: an empty name/version, zero declared capabilities (an app that asks for nothing could never be admitted to anything), a capability with a zero rights mask (meaningless, and would otherwise refuse silently forever at admission rather than loudly at the manifest boundary), and a zero iteration bound (TAME root rule 2's own bounded-loop discipline, checked here rather than left as a confusing runtime failure downstream).
think Hit and fixed a real compile error on the first build: buf_len_u32 was typed for []const u8 only, and I called it on a []const DeclaredCapability slice when setting cap_count. Added a generic slice_len_u32(comptime T, buf: []const T) rather than casting around the type mismatch, since the two callers (byte-buffer lengths vs capability-array length) are genuinely different shapes and deserve their own named helper rather than one function pretending to handle both.
think Ran the new witness directly after building -- all eight claims printed GREEN in order, the exact sequence designed (one welcome path, then declares()'s own three checks, then five distinct malformed refusals) -- before wiring anything into the larger suite, so the isolated build-and-run proof came first and the suite integration came second.
think Wrote tools/tube0_manifest_witness.rish mirroring tools/pool_host_seam_witness.rish's own shape (build, run, assert GREEN plus specific named substrings for the welcome and unwelcome paths) rather than inventing a new witness-wrapper style. Appended the new call to tools/parity_ch01.rish at the exact tail the file already ends at, after the rune bounded-trap witness -- the newest lap belongs at the newest position, matching every other addition in that file's own history.
think Ran the full tools/parity_ch01.rish chapter end to end after wiring TUBE0 in, rather than trusting the isolated witness alone -- this is a large, genuinely slow suite (over 600 seconds, rebuilding dozens of witnesses including a Wayland/Brushstroke component from source), so let it run in the background and checked on it periodically rather than blocking the whole turn on it.
think The suite came back RED, not GREEN -- named plainly rather than glossed over, and investigated immediately rather than assumed benign. tools/tame_style_check.rish flagged a banned copyForwards idiom in four files. Confirmed via git log on each of the four individually (not assumed as one batch) that none were touched this session -- three dated 20260715 within an eight-minute window, one dated 20260714 -- and confirmed my own two new .rye files contain no occurrence of the banned idiom at all. This is a real, pre-existing red this session did not cause and was not asked to fix; named it honestly in TASKS.md with the exact files and dates rather than silently patching scope beyond what was asked, or worse, silently claiming the suite is fully green when it is not.
think Answered the broader strategic question in the same turn, honestly rather than optimistically: the rune/syntax spec (active-designing/20260716-033000) is a real design document with one genuinely checkable half (the RISC-V codegen claim, which quotes real disassembly of hand-written code matching the proposed expansion's shape) and no parser or lowering pass at all -- every "Glow" artifact in this tree today, TUBE0 included, is actually hand-written Rye/Zig standing in for what Glow's own syntax would eventually compile to, not the real thing. Recommended against starting reference-grade docs or beginner tutorials yet, citing this tree's own docs-implementation-sync root rule (a doc describing behavior the code doesn't have is exactly the thing the rule warns against) and naming the concrete next step the rune brief itself already scoped: a small real parser prototype for just the bounded |- form.
obs TUBE0 is the first artifact in this whole tree that is genuinely application-layer Glow design (a manifest an app would carry) rather than kernel/language substrate (Nock, the rune grammar, Pool's own host seam) -- a real, if small, step past where the tree's Glow-application-framework thread stood this morning.
